post_text:
The Gettysburg Area High School Witness Award is a recognition that is annually bestowed upon a deserving senior of the graduating class, who possesses a passion for the history that defines our town. The winner of the 2020 Witness Award is Ava Sonnett.

This Minie Ball statuette issued to the recipient of the award, is appropriately crafted out of wood from a tree that watched the Battle of Gettysburg unfold more than 150 years ago, many of them still standing today, as constant reminders of the struggle that took place here. Those trees are referred to as Witness Trees, and they are the inspiration behind this recognition.

Congratulations, Ava! #GASDisGreat

Each year the Gettysburg Area High School Visual & Media Art Department chooses two Senior All-Stars. This year‚Äôs stars go to the following seniors (in alphabetical order):

Mackenzie Monn
Molly Stover

This award is determined based on three areas of excellence and achievement in the arts.

1. Academic achievement (GPA)
2. Arts leadership (#Warriorway - attendance & commitment to studies)
3. Community outreach (Murals, publications, backdrops, studio and school arts support)

This year, these two seniors also went above and beyond in the Arts while the Coronavirus pandemic prompted virtual remote learning. We are proud to recognize their accomplishments with the Art Department pin to wear proudly on your graduation gown. #GASDisGreat

We have received word that a company (unsure of the name at this point) is calling our local businesses to try to get donations for masks for our football team that would include our Warrior logo along with individual business logos. Please know this is NOT one of our football fundraisers and that the district and athletic program is NOT sponsoring such solicitation. We do not want our local businesses taken advantage of.

Please feel free to share to alert our local businesses. Thank you for your help.

Gettysburg Area Retail Merchants Association The Chamber of Gettysburg & Adams County

Gettysburg Area Elementary Schools held a virtual field day today. Take a look at some of the photos of students practicing during the days leading up to the virtual field day.

All three, health and physical education teachers had a field day Zoom session with each grade level with our school's students throughout the day. Along with a large variety of field day activities for the students to do, the art teachers added slides to make Olympic torches, and headbands, the music teachers started field day Zooms off with the "Star-Spangled Banner", and the librarians read stories about Olympic athletes.

#GASDisGreat

post_text:
The Shippensburg University AuthorShip, sponsored by Sigma Tau Delta, received over 150 entries this year and Gettysburg Area Middle School students clinched two second place spots.

Congratulations to eighth-grader Craig (CJ) Lair "The Day the Sun Left" in poetry writing and eighth-grader Michael Wilson - "Tiny Redwood" in fictional writing.

Each student won a monetary prize and will be invited to attend next year's award ceremony at Shippensburg University. Their writings will also be published in the annual anthology. Congratulations, students! #GASDisGreat

During Art Learning in Mrs. Myers' high school classes, students study the interview processes of Lebanese artist, Mounira Al Solh and visual statements of street artists such as Haring, Fairey and Basquiat as well as creative stop motion Vimeo animator Kirsten Lepor and humorous photographer, Terry Border, then take off to create with what they have at home.

This is the first of a series of students documenting creatively the thoughts and visuals happening in their environment of quarantine COVID-19. #GASDisGreat

post_text: Students participating in remote elementary gifted-support were asked to use the Google Earth "feeling lucky" function to virtually travel to a random location. Once there, they conducted research and answered grade-level specific questions about the location. Finally, they created travel brochures to inform potential tourists of their location's features. They used Canva and ReadWriteThink to make their brochures digitally or could make one using paper and art supplies. They collaborated via Padlet, Zoom, and FlipGrid during the process. #GASDisGreat

Warrior Care and Connect
March 25 at 3:59 PM ¬∑

PMHCA and Youth MOVE PA are offering ‚Äúvirtual check-in‚Äù zoom meetings to help reduce the sense of social isolation we can experience during this difficult time. One topic that is off-limits is the COVID-19 virus!

The ‚ÄúAdult Virtual Drop-In‚Äù, is a topic-driven, social gathering hour that is scheduled twice a week. We would love to discuss many different topics such as our ‚Äúfavorite things‚Äù and our ‚Äúgo to coping skills‚Äù with whoever wants to join us. Meetings will take place using Zoom on Tuesday and Thursday from 1 pm to 2 pm.

Youth MOVE PA is excited to host a ‚ÄúYouth Virtual Drop-In‚Äù that is all about getting some social Interaction. We will be talking about ourselves, what we like, and be discussing a specific topic with each other during each meeting. Our meetings will be hosted every Monday and Friday from 1pm to 2pm on Zoom.

Meeting ID: 131-337-859, Meeting Link: https://zoom.us/j/131337859

post_text:
Gettysburg Area School District is celebrating 50 years of Outdoor Education Camp this fall. Amazing! We want our celebration to be a special one, and a great way to make it special is for former campers to get involved! Please consider sharing your camp stories, photos, videos and artifacts (quiet-spot markers, sit-a-pons, camp t-shirts, etc.) at a special ceremony in September. The older the pictures and artifacts are the better!

Share your stories, photos, videos at communications@gasd-pa.org. If you have artifacts that you would be willing to display during the ceremony this fall, please let us know in an email too. We will borrow them for the ceremony and return them afterward.

GASD would especially love to hear from Camp Hemlock 1971 alumni. If you were a camper, counselor or teacher from 1971 and are willing to talk about that first camp, be sure to respond.

Help us spread the word by sharing this news with family, friends and coworkers. We look forward to celebrating 50 years of camp with you! #GASDisGreat
text:
Gettysburg Area School District is celebrating 50 years of Outdoor Education Camp this fall. Amazing! We want our celebration to be a special one, and a great way to make it special is for former campers to get involved! Please consider sharing your camp stories, photos, videos and artifacts (quiet-spot markers, sit-a-pons, camp t-shirts, etc.) at a special ceremony in September. The older the pictures and artifacts are the better!

Share your stories, photos, videos at communications@gasd-pa.org. If you have artifacts that you would be willing to display during the ceremony this fall, please let us know in an email too. We will borrow them for the ceremony and return them afterward.

GASD would especially love to hear from Camp Hemlock 1971 alumni. If you were a camper, counselor or teacher from 1971 and are willing to talk about that first camp, be sure to respond.

Help us spread the word by sharing this news with family, friends and coworkers. We look forward to celebrating 50 years of camp with you! #GASDisGreat

post_text:
Under the supervision and guidance of Mr. Justin Klingler, eleven 8th grade students attended the 2020 Middle School K'Nex Design Challenge held at IU12. Students had to work together to plan, design, and build a model of a solution to help conserve energy for the future. Students were judged on creativity, teamwork, challenge success, design, and presentation. They also needed to submit blueprints, a journal, a 2-minute presentation and a budget assessment. Each group was judged by several adults who asked very challenging questions! All three teams did outstanding work but two teams won awards.

Molly Heaton, Grace Stone, CJ Lair, and Connar Woodward won third place overall! Maddy Hassinger, Tristan Smith, Zach Aumen, Addison Yingling won the award to Best Teamwork! Congratulations to all the students and to Mr. Klingler for his support and guidance! #GASDisGreat

The girls basketball team was recognized as this year's girls team to win the Gretchen Wolf Swartz Award. This is a prestigious award that focuses on the sportsmanship of athletic teams.

At the conclusion of each regular season, York area basketball officials vote to recognize a boys‚Äô and girls‚Äô program after observing the season-long conduct of Y-A players, fans, faculty, students, managers, coaches and cheerleaders from the junior high through the varsity level. Both winning programs receive a traveling trophy in recognition of their accomplishments. Our 4 girls basketball seniors are now eligible to apply for up to a combined $50,000 in scholarship money.

Our girls have not only been successful on the court in the win/loss column (21-2 overall) but have done it the right way. #GASDisGreat

post_text:
Congratulations to our #GASDGlows Winners for November 2019! GASD Glows is a program that highlights Gettysburg‚Äôs greatest employees, volunteers and community partners. Awardees were chosen for embodying the district‚Äôs mission and vision statements. To nominate an employee, volunteer or community partner, go to gettysburg.k12.pa.us/glows. #GASDisGreat

Top, from left: Dr. Jason Perrin, superintendent; Jane Collins, superintendent's secretary and Andrew Robinson, communications coordinator. Jane received the award for her remarkable passion for helping others-- even going as far as giving her cell phone number out to co-workers to contact her on days she isn't at work.

Bottom, from left: Asha Withers, high school academic support teacher; Andrew Robinson, communications coordinator and Colleen Muhl, intervention paraprofessional. Asha and Colleen were dually nominated for their work with high school students who need a little extra love and support as they work to meet academic expectations. These individuals provide care, support, attention and a little tough love when needed.

post_text: Congratulations to the following editors: Taylor Woodward, Courtney Servant, Josie Urban, Shea Brockett, Anna Coale, Patricia Buxton, Morgan Ramsburg, William Shafer and Elizabeth Bigham of the 2019 Cannon-Aid yearbook. This group of editors swapped hats of responsibility as classes changed between semesters and were awarded the second place in the 2019 American Scholastic Press Association High School Yearbook and Magazine Competition. Taylor Woodward masterminded and designed an amazing cover and page templates and was supported by Courtney Servant. The remaining team of editors led an additional 30 students to success in spite of grueling software problems related to the publication company's software. The editors and staff overcame odds that epitomize Warrior Tenacity and Spirit. #GASDisGreat #WarriorWay

December 4, 2019 at 5:07 PM ¬∑

The Gettysburg Area Education Foundation (GAEF) seeks candidates for Foundation Director. This is a part-time Independent Contractor position with overall strategic and operational responsibility for the Foundation‚Äôs fundraising, programs, and execution of its mission. The director collaborates with Foundation officers, board, and committee members to meet annual budgetary and program goals and facilitates grant preparation and management. The director serves as the Foundation‚Äôs representative, promoting the Foundation‚Äôs mission within the community and school district, and reports to the Foundation President and Executive Committee.

For additional information regarding this exciting position please visit the GAEF website at gettysburgwarriorfunds.org.

Out of the 80 classes that qualified from around South Central PA, Mrs. Ryder's class came in 3rd place, and Mr. Haffey's class came in 1st place! Mr. Haffey's class also featured two students who finished the contest in the top ten performing students! Congratulations to Morgan Redding, 9th place, and to Blake Haines who came in 7th place! #GASDisGreat

The middle school cross country team sponsored a Mini-Thon fun run event around the Spangler Springs loop. Both senior high and middle school students organized the 2.8 mile run with 10 challenge stations with one station pieing Principal, Mrs. Herb in the face. The event raised $1,600 for the Four Diamonds Foundation to fight childhood cancer.

Special THANKS to the following: MS Principal Herb, the Middle School Teachers and staff, HS Principal Lusk, Mrs. Caywood, DJ Zeigler, AAR Plastics, Gettysburg National Parks Service, the high school Mini Thon committee, Technology Student Association and all those that participated. #GASDisGreat
